HAIDER ACKERMANN PARA JEAN PAUL GAULTIER
Ayer, al hilo del post sobre #JeanPaulGaultier, me acordé de que os debía, desde hace meses, esta crónica que ahora estoy escribiendo.

A finales de enero de este año se presentaba, dentro de la semana parisina de la #AltaCostura, la colección de primavera 2023 de Gaultier. Lo que lleva haciendo el irreverente maestro, desde que se retiró hace un par de años, es ceder la pasarela a un renombrado diseñador para que desfile bajo su etiqueta. Después de Olivier Rousteing, de Balmain, Glenn Martens de Y/Project y Chitose Abe de Sacai, el cuarto ha sido el diseñador francés (aunque nacido en Colombia en 1971) Haider Ackermann.

La colección de Ackermann fue absolutamente fascinante, auténtica #hautecouture no solo por la hechura de las prendas (sastrería impecable, siluetas arquitectónicas, cromatismo equilibrado) sino por la forma en la que las modelos movían las prendas por la pasarela, con la cadencia y los movimientos de la época dorada de la Alta Costura. Las dosis justas, a partes iguales, de dramatismo y minimalismo en la que fue probablemente una de las colecciones más celebradas por la crítica de toda la temporada, la consagración definitiva de #HaiderAckermann (yo leí comentarios que pedían para él la dirección creativa de Balenciaga 😍) y, sin duda, una de las mejores colecciones de la firma #Gaultier de los últimos años.

Our second cover story for @elledecor’s April Designers At Home issue is the pared-back Lisbon pied-à-terre of jewelry star Matthew Harris, founder of the brand @mateonewyork. A longtime fascination with the work of Alexander Calder (spawned by a childhood interest in Calder’s mobile sculpture “Flight”) led him to collect a 1975 Calder wall-hanging in jute, with the help of an art advisor. The piece then became a central element of his Portugal pad. Obviously, I’m a fan of Harris’s emerald-hued home office, hello. But the Andrew Neyer chandelier, from @trnknyc, in the living room and the hand-painted Portuguese tile in the bathroom are favorites of mine, too. Also, we share some news: next up for Harris? Decorative accessories for the home. Get more details and the full story, beautifully written by @elledecor contributing editor for jewelry @tanyadukes, in the issue now and at ElleDecor.com. Carole Feuerman's iconic swimmers are on view in New York City with a monumental exhibition on Park Avenue and a solo show at Galeries Bartoux New York.

Installed outdoors until December 10, 2023, nine of Feuerman's hyper-realistic sculptures can be seen from 34th to 39th Park Avenue in New York. Exploring classicism and beauty in contemporary art, a pioneer of hyperrealism, Feuerman is known for her lifelike “Swimmers” sculptures. Experience the breathtaking realism of the artworks up close, right down to the drops of water leaking onto the skin of the swimmers.

My first real significant find as a design collector was not Danish, American, or even mid-century. It was a proto-modernist chair by #OttoWagner (exactly like this one from Van Ham). 

I used to mine this place called Antiques Warehouse on Princess Street, mainly for a seemingly unending supply of Eames fibreglass on the 5th floor. I started to venture to the other floors and buried under a dusty pile of generic bentwood chairs was this one. It looked vaguely familiar so I took a chance, paid $60, and brought it home. I researched it and was ecstatic to find I had something very important, designed by someone hugely important. Ended up selling it privately to a collector in Miami a few months later for 3k. 

Looking back, finding and researching this chair really set the stage for my own design taste and my own practice. It gave me an appreciation for history, taught me how everything is connected, and that chips and scratches can be beautiful things because they tell the story of the piece.

ON STAGE THIS SPRING // A seminal work in the development of Balanchine’s distinct approach to neoclassicism and one of the ballets featured on the Company’s debut program in 1948, Concerto Barocco returns to the NYCB stage after a nearly five-year hiatus. Set to Bach’s Concerto for Two Violins in D minor or Double Violin Concerto, the work features two lead dancers corresponding to the score’s soloists. According to Balanchine, Concerto Barocco “has no ‘subject matter’ beyond the score to which it is danced and the particular dancers who execute it”; as such, the ornate, Baroque-inspired Eugene Berman costumes created for the ballet’s initial performances were jettisoned in 1951 to allow the choreography to speak for itself. Concerto Barocco is now performed in simple practice clothes, making it one of, if not the, first of Balanchine’s so-called Black & White ballets.⁠

Part 1 - December 1st, 2012. This little guy was born in Pennsylvania. This image is the picture the breeder posted of him. I fell in love with him instantly. March 2013 he came home and became a New Yorker. He was a total punk. Ran all over the house. Went under the sofa all the time and hated the snow. Snowy days… forget about it. He was hard to train and was super hyper. But he his personality was amazing from the get go.  A loving puppy eager to please and play catch in the long hallways of the apartment building. Eleven years ago watching the Oscars he became Clooney after George Clooney. #happybirthday #perfectpuppy #clooney #humandog.

Part 2 - Then he became a Puerto Rico doggie. Pampered and spoiled by everyone that saw him. He became a young man and his perfect manners charmed everyone. Almost lost him on his second year in San Juan when he ran out of the store and a car pinched literally his hair. That was a nightmare. Like his Dad he is a fashionista with bandannas and ties around his neck. His big brown eyes are human eyes and when he looks at you is like he is speaking to you.  Always friendly and sweet. Yet stubborn and always getting in the trash! 🙄

Part 3 - Then came his little brother Cooper and since the moment they met, they are inseparable. Can’t take one without the other. I am so grateful to have such amazing kids. Clooney has been with me since I got here. Through thick and thin giving me unconditional love every single day. Every day I am thankful for his presence in my life. Always there and full of love and affection. Today he turns 11 and my love for him grows more and more each day. #blessed #humandogs #clooney #cooper #happybirthday
